<subSubSection id="679A654DFF860166ECB36863E6AC037E" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="description">
<paragraph id="2F3F36C6FF860166ECB36863E538048D" blockId="18.[136,1452,563,1526]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis id="1DF4EAD4FF860166ECB36863E73A0575" bold="true" box="[189,327,563,589]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Description</emphasis>
:—Herbs, annual, with taproot. Stems prostrate, mat-forming, 
<quantity id="E8789B23FF860166E8056863E20C0576" box="[1035,1137,563,590]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="cm" value="22.5" valueMax="40.0" valueMin="5.0">5–40 cm</quantity>
, glabrous. Leaves opposite; stipules distinct, linear to subulate, usually irregularly fimbriate or lobed, 0.4–2.0 mm, glabrous; petiole 0.2–2.0 mm, glabrous; blade narrowly oblong to oblong-obovate, 3–15 × 
<quantity id="E8789B23FF860166EF31682CE5DD05AE" box="[831,928,636,662]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="4.5" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="2.0">2–7 mm</quantity>
, base asymmetric, margins sparsely serrulate, especially near apex, apex rounded to obtuse, abaxial surface usually pale greyish, adaxial surface sometimes with reddish spot, both surfaces glabrous; palmately veined at base, pinnate distally. Cyathia solitary or in small, cymose clusters at distal nodes. Involucre obconic, 0.6–0.9 × 
<quantity id="E8789B23FF860166EEDC68B7E527043A" box="[722,858,743,770]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="0.44999999999999996" valueMax="0.6" valueMin="0.3">0.3–0.6 mm</quantity>
, glabrous; glands 4, red or purplish, narrowly oblongelliptic, 0.1–0.2 × 
<quantity id="E8789B23FF860166ED57695BE798041E" box="[345,485,779,806]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="0.3" valueMax="0.5" valueMin="0.1">0.1–0.5 mm</quantity>
; appendages white to pink, semilunate and fringing distal margin of gland, 0.1–0.3 × 
<quantity id="E8789B23FF860166EC866960E76D0472" box="[136,272,816,842]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="0.2" valueMax="0.3" valueMin="0.1">0.1–0.3 mm</quantity>
, distal margin crenulate or lobed. Staminate flowers 1–5. Pistillate flowers: ovary glabrous; styles 
<quantity id="E8789B23FF860166E9596960E6CB0456" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="0.2" valueMax="0.3" valueMin="0.1">0.1–0.3 mm</quantity>
, 2-fid ½ length. Capsules ovoid, 1.3–1.9 × 1.6–2.0 mm, glabrous; columella 
<quantity id="E8789B23FF860166E8266903E2C90456" box="[1064,1204,851,878]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="1.4" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="1.3">1.3–1.5 mm</quantity>
. Seeds with caduceus white coat, testa tan brown, oblong-ovoid, sharply angular in cross section, 1.0–1.4 × 
<quantity id="E8789B23FF860166E8746927E37A04AA" box="[1146,1287,887,914]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="0.75" valueMax="0.9" valueMin="0.6">0.6–0.9 mm</quantity>
, with 3–4(–6) prominent transverse ridges that usually interrupt abaxial keel.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2F3F36C6FF860166ECB36990E6A004C6" blockId="18.[136,1452,563,1526]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis id="1DF4EAD4FF860166ECB36990E72804E2" bold="true" box="[189,341,960,986]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Iconography</emphasis>
:— 
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166ED7869EFE44904E2" author="Taylor, N. C." box="[374,564,959,986]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refId="ref34663" refString="Taylor, N. C. (2016) Explorations into Euphorbia sect. Anisophyllum (Euphorbiaceae) in the trans-Pecos region of Texas with a focus on the Fendleri Clade. Sul Ross State University, 76 pp." type="book" year="2016">Taylor (2016: 24</bibRefCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="B7BB2A43FF860166EE3069EFE4E104E2" box="[574,668,959,986]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="10.[136,229,1872,1894]" captionTargetBox="[251,1334,285,1847]" captionTargetId="figure-63@10.[250,1335,284,1848]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5. Euphorbia berteroana:A) exsiccatum from Guadaloupe preserved at TO, B) detail of terminal glomerule with short peduncle (scale = 0.5 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5422313" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5422313/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Figure 5</figureCitation>
), 
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166EEBE69EFE51304E2" author="Jercinovic, E." box="[688,878,959,986]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="1 - 14" refId="ref30744" refString="Jercinovic, E. (2007) The status of the genus Chamaesyce in New Mexico. The New Mexico Botanist 40: 1 - 14." type="journal article" year="2007">Jercinovic (2007</bibRefCitation>
: pl. 10, under the name 
<taxonomicName id="E8804D45FF860166E87E69EFE3E604E1" authorityName="Small" authorityYear="1903" baseAuthorityName="Engelm." box="[1136,1435,959,985]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Chamaesyce" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="glyptosperma">
<emphasis id="1DF4EAD4FF860166E87E69EFE3E604E1" box="[1136,1435,959,985]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Chamaesyce glyptosperma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), Fig. 11.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2F3F36C6FF860166ECB36E57E6AC037E" blockId="18.[136,1452,563,1526]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis id="1DF4EAD4FF860166ECB36E57E7BB031A" bold="true" box="[189,454,1031,1058]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Chromosome number</emphasis>
:—2n = 22 (
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166EE576E57E522031A" author="Steinmann, V. W. &amp; Morawetz, J. J. &amp; Berry, P. E. &amp; Peirson, J. A. &amp; Yang, Y." box="[601,863,1031,1058]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="251 - 293" refId="ref34413" refString="Steinmann, V. W., Morawetz, J. J., Berry, P. E., Peirson, J. A. &amp; Yang, Y. (2016) Euphorbia Linnaeus sect. Anisophyllum Roeper. In: Rabeler, R. K. &amp; Hartman, R. L. (Eds.) Flora of North America 12. Oxford University Press, New York, Oxford, pp. 251 - 293." type="book chapter" year="2016">
Steinmann 
<emphasis id="1DF4EAD4FF860166EED36E58E5650319" box="[733,792,1031,1057]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
); n = 11 (
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166EFDB6E57E224031A" author="Ward, D. E." box="[981,1113,1031,1058]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="302 - 309" refId="ref35468" refString="Ward, D. E. (1983) Chromosome counts from New Mexico and southern Colorado. Phytologia 54: 302 - 309. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 14424" type="journal article" year="1983">Ward 1983</bibRefCitation>
); n = 10, 12 (
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166E8F16E57E6B9037E" author="Urbatsch, L. E. &amp; Bacon, J. D. &amp; Hartman, R. L. &amp; Johnston, M. C. &amp; Watson Jr, T. J. &amp; Webster, G. L." pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="494 - 500" refId="ref35109" refString="Urbatsch, L. E., Bacon, J. D., Hartman, R. L., Johnston, M. C., Watson Jr, T. J. &amp; Webster, G. L. (1975) Chromosome numbers for North American Euphorbiaceae. American Journal of Botany 62: 494 - 500. https: // doi. org / 10.1002 / j. 1537 - 2197.1975. tb 14075. x" type="journal article" year="1975">
Urbatsch 
<emphasis id="1DF4EAD4FF860166E97E6E58E3D10319" box="[1392,1452,1031,1057]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
1975
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="679A654DFF860166ECB36E00E22D02CD" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="2F3F36C6FF860166ECB36E00E32303B6" blockId="18.[136,1452,563,1526]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis id="1DF4EAD4FF860166ECB36E00E7610352" bold="true" box="[189,284,1104,1130]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Ecology</emphasis>
:—Accidentally dispersed by humans and vehicles as contaminant. It colonizes stream and riverbanks, sand prairies, loess hill prairies, meadows, ballast, open disturbed areas and roadsides (
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166E85B6E23E32F03B6" author="Steinmann, V. W. &amp; Morawetz, J. J. &amp; Berry, P. E. &amp; Peirson, J. A. &amp; Yang, Y." box="[1109,1362,1139,1166]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="251 - 293" refId="ref34413" refString="Steinmann, V. W., Morawetz, J. J., Berry, P. E., Peirson, J. A. &amp; Yang, Y. (2016) Euphorbia Linnaeus sect. Anisophyllum Roeper. In: Rabeler, R. K. &amp; Hartman, R. L. (Eds.) Flora of North America 12. Oxford University Press, New York, Oxford, pp. 251 - 293." type="book chapter" year="2016">
Steinmann 
<emphasis id="1DF4EAD4FF860166E8D86E24E37303B5" box="[1238,1294,1139,1165]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2F3F36C6FF860166ECB36EC7E5CE02B2" blockId="18.[136,1452,563,1526]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis id="1DF4EAD4FF860166ECB36EC7E72D038A" bold="true" box="[189,336,1175,1202]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Alien status</emphasis>
:—Neophyte species native to the New World, it can be considered naturalized in 
<collectingCountry id="57977656FF860166E93D6EC7E3150389" box="[1331,1384,1175,1201]" name="Italy" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Italy</collectingCountry>
. First European occurrences as casual presences were from 
<collectingCountry id="57977656FF860166EEE66EEBE53C03ED" box="[744,833,1211,1237]" name="Sweden" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Sweden</collectingCountry>
in 1911 (
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166EFA36EEBE25203EE" author="Blom, C." box="[941,1071,1211,1238]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="45 - 47" refId="ref26948" refString="Blom, C. (1912) Invandrare. Botaniska Notiser 65: 45 - 47." type="journal article" year="1912">Blom 1912</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166E8356EECE20903EE" author="Blom, C." box="[1083,1140,1212,1238]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="213 - 214" refId="ref26965" refString="Blom, C. (1919) Om nagra Amarantus - fynd i Sverige. Botaniska Notiser 72: 213 - 214." type="journal article" year="1919">1919</bibRefCitation>
) and from 
<collectingCountry id="57977656FF860166E8FD6EEBE33003ED" box="[1267,1357,1211,1237]" name="Netherlands" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Holland</collectingCountry>
in 1916 (
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166EC9E6E8FE75703C2" author="Hugin, G." box="[144,298,1247,1274]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="189 - 223" refId="ref30332" refString="Hugin, G. (1998 b) Die Gattung Chamaesyce in Europa. Bestimmungsschlussel mit taxonomisch-nomenklatorischen Anmerkungen. Feddes Repertorium 109: 189 - 223. https: // doi. org / 10.1002 / fedr. 4921090302" type="journal article" year="1998">Hügin 1998b</bibRefCitation>
). Since the 1964 the species was recorded in 
<collectingCountry id="57977656FF860166EF256E8FE50003C1" box="[811,893,1247,1273]" name="Austria" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Austria</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166EF836E8FE2D103C2" author="Hugin, G. &amp; Starlinger, F." box="[909,1196,1247,1274]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="112 - 117" refId="ref30488" refString="Hugin, G. &amp; Starlinger, F. (1998) Erstnachweis fur Chamaesyce glyptosperma in Mitteleuropa (mit Berucksichtigung der ubrigen europaischen Vorkommen). Floristische Rundbriefe. Zeitschrift fur floristische Geobotanik, Populationsokologie und Systematik 31: 112 - 117." type="journal article" year="1998">Hügin &amp; Starlinger 1998</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingCountry id="57977656FF860166E8CF6EB0E37003C2" box="[1217,1293,1248,1274]" name="France" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">France</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166E9136EB0E3E203C2" author="Roux, J. P." box="[1309,1439,1248,1274]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="4 - 8" refId="ref33482" refString="Roux, J. P. (1992) Euphorbia glyptosperma Engelm., taxon nouveau pour la flore de France. Le Monde des Plantes 443: 4 - 8." type="journal article" year="1992">Roux 1992</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingCountry id="57977656FF860166EC866F53E7EF0225" box="[136,402,1283,1309]" name="Macedonia" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Republic of Macedonia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166EDAD6F53E4B80226" author="Hugin, G. &amp; Starlinger, F." box="[419,709,1283,1310]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="112 - 117" refId="ref30488" refString="Hugin, G. &amp; Starlinger, F. (1998) Erstnachweis fur Chamaesyce glyptosperma in Mitteleuropa (mit Berucksichtigung der ubrigen europaischen Vorkommen). Floristische Rundbriefe. Zeitschrift fur floristische Geobotanik, Populationsokologie und Systematik 31: 112 - 117." type="journal article" year="1998">Hügin &amp; Starlinger 1998</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingCountry id="57977656FF860166EED56F53E5730225" box="[731,782,1283,1309]" name="Italy" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Italy</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166EF116F53E2640226" author="Hugin, G. &amp; Hugin, H." box="[799,1049,1283,1310]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="61" refId="ref30455" refString="Hugin, G. &amp; Hugin, H. (1999) Segnalazioni Floristiche Italiane: 904. Chamaesyce glyptosperma (Engelm.) Small. Informatore Botanico Italiano 30: 61." type="journal article" year="1999">Hügin &amp; Hügin 1999</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingCountry id="57977656FF860166E8216F54E2EC0226" box="[1071,1169,1284,1310]" name="Hungary" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Hungary</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166E8AF6F53E3360226" author="Somlyay, L." box="[1185,1355,1283,1310]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="23 - 32" refId="ref34146" refString="Somlyay, L. (2009) Occurrence of Chamaesyce glyptosperma, and a survey of the genus Chamaesyce (Euphorbiaceae) in Hungary. Annales historico-naturales Musei nationalis hungarici 101: 23 - 32." type="journal article" year="2009">Somlyay 2009</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingCountry id="57977656FF860166E96F6F53E3D10225" box="[1377,1452,1283,1309]" name="Russia" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Russia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166EC9E6F77E79D027A" author="Geltman, D. V. &amp; Medvedeva, N. A." box="[144,480,1319,1346]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="131 - 135" refId="ref29433" refString="Geltman, D. V. &amp; Medvedeva, N. A. (2017) Euphorbia glyptosperma (Euphorbiaceae) - нovый cuziрodный vid dлi флoры Рoссii. Euphorbia glyptosperma (Euphorbiaceae), an alien species new for the flora of Russia. НOVOсti сiсtiмatiKi Vысsik рaсtiнiй - Novitates Systematicae Plantarum Vascularium 48: 131 - 135." type="journal article" year="2017">Geltman &amp; Medvedeva 2017</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingCountry id="57977656FF860166EDFB6F77E4270279" box="[501,602,1319,1345]" name="Romania" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Romania</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166EE646F77E521027A" author="Sirbu, C. &amp; Susnia, I." box="[618,860,1319,1348]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="135 - 144" refId="ref34012" refString="Sirbu, C. &amp; Susnia, I. (2018) New records in the alien flora of Romania: Euphorbia serpens and E. glyptosperma. Journal of Plant Development 25: 135 - 144. https: // doi. org / 10.33628 / jpd. 2018.25.1.135" type="journal article" year="2018">Sîrbu &amp; Șușnia 2018</bibRefCitation>
) and doubtfully in 
<collectingCountry id="57977656FF860166E8366F77E2C30279" box="[1080,1214,1319,1345]" name="Switzerland" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Switzerland</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166E8C06F77E6BE025E" author="Hugin, G. &amp; Starlinger, F." pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="112 - 117" refId="ref30488" refString="Hugin, G. &amp; Starlinger, F. (1998) Erstnachweis fur Chamaesyce glyptosperma in Mitteleuropa (mit Berucksichtigung der ubrigen europaischen Vorkommen). Floristische Rundbriefe. Zeitschrift fur floristische Geobotanik, Populationsokologie und Systematik 31: 112 - 117." type="journal article" year="1998">Hügin &amp; Starlinger 1998</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166ECC36F1BE7D4025E" author="Rothlisberger, J." box="[205,425,1355,1382]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="19 - 33" refId="ref33456" refString="Rothlisberger, J. (2007) Aktuelle Verbreitung der Gattung Chamaesyce (Euphorbiaceae) in der Schweiz. Bauhinia 20: 19 - 33." type="journal article" year="2007">Röthlisberger 2007</bibRefCitation>
). Its alien status in Europe is uncertain, but it can be considered as naturalized in many cases (
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166EC9E6F3FE7FE02B2" author="Hugin, G. &amp; Hugin, H." box="[144,387,1391,1418]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="61" refId="ref30455" refString="Hugin, G. &amp; Hugin, H. (1999) Segnalazioni Floristiche Italiane: 904. Chamaesyce glyptosperma (Engelm.) Small. Informatore Botanico Italiano 30: 61." type="journal article" year="1999">Hügin &amp; Hügin 1999</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166ED806F3FE4CB02B2" author="Tison, J. M. &amp; Foucault, B. de" box="[398,694,1391,1418]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refId="ref34813" refString="Tison, J. M. &amp; Foucault, B. de (2014) Flora gallica: flore de France. Biotope, 1195 pp." type="book" year="2014">Tison &amp; de Foucault 2014</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="4B114B37FF860166EECE6F3FE5DA02B2" author="Wolf, M. &amp; Kiraly, G." box="[704,935,1391,1418]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="243 - 250" refId="ref35754" refString="Wolf, M. &amp; Kiraly, G. (2014) Euphorbia serpens (Euphorbiaceae), a new alien species in Hungary. Acta Botanica Hungarica 56: 243 - 250. https: // doi. org / 10.1556 / ABot. 56.2014.1 - 2.16" type="journal article" year="2014">Wolf &amp; Király 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2F3F36C6FF860166ECB36FC3E51C0296" blockId="18.[136,1452,563,1526]" box="[189,865,1427,1454]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis id="1DF4EAD4FF860166ECB36FC3E7DB0296" bold="true" box="[189,422,1427,1454]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Occurrence in 
<collectingCountry id="57977656FF860166ED606FC4E7DB0296" box="[366,422,1428,1454]" name="Italy" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Italy</collectingCountry>
</emphasis>
:—Naturalized in PIE, LOM and EMR.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2F3F36C6FF860166ECB36FE7E22D02CD" blockId="18.[136,1452,563,1526]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis id="1DF4EAD4FF860166ECB36FE7E7A902E9" bold="true" box="[189,468,1463,1489]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Taxonomic annotations</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName id="E8804D45FF860166EDF66FE7E57202E9" box="[504,783,1463,1489]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Euphorbia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="glyptosperma">
<emphasis id="1DF4EAD4FF860166EDF66FE7E57202E9" box="[504,783,1463,1489]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Euphorbia glyptosperma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="E8804D45FF860166EFAD6FE8E25702E9" box="[931,1066,1463,1489]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Euphorbia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humifusa">
<emphasis id="1DF4EAD4FF860166EFAD6FE8E25702E9" box="[931,1066,1463,1489]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">E. humifusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it can be easily discriminated by seed ornamentation. It can also be confused with glabrous forms of 
<emphasis id="1DF4EAD4FF860166EFAC6F8CE22D02CD" box="[930,1104,1499,1525]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<taxonomicName id="E8804D45FF860166EFAC6F8CE23102CD" box="[930,1100,1499,1525]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Euphorbia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chamaesyce">E. chamaesyce</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
